1. Understanding the TCP Handshake (3-Way Handshake)

TCP is a connection-oriented protocol. Before any data is exchanged, both devices (client and server) must agree to communicate.
This is done using the three-way handshake:

Step 1 — SYN (Client → Server)

Frame 1 in Wireshark.

TCP flags: SYN = 1

Purpose:

Client says: “I want to start a connection.”

Client sends:

Initial Sequence Number (ISN)

TCP Options (MSS, SACK, Window Scale, Timestamps, etc.)

Options in the SYN packet:

You will see these inside the TCP Header → Options section:

MSS (Maximum Segment Size): Typically 1460 bytes

SACK Permitted: Allows selective ACK

Window Scale: Needed for large windows

Timestamps: Used for RTT, PAWS

NOP (No-Operation): Padding bytes to make sure TCP header is a multiple of 4 bytes (because TCP header must be 32 bits aligned)

This makes the TCP header bigger (e.g., 40 bytes instead of 20).

Step 2 — SYN-ACK (Server → Client)

Frame 2 in Wireshark.

TCP flags: SYN = 1, ACK = 1

Purpose:

Server acknowledges the client’s SYN: “I received your request.”

Server sends its own SYN: “I also want to connect.”

Server sends its chosen TCP Options.

Again, header often ~40 bytes.

Step 3 — ACK (Client → Server)

Frame 3 in Wireshark.

TCP flags: ACK = 1

Purpose:

Client acknowledges the server’s SYN.

Now the connection is established.

TCP header size now smaller (~20–32 bytes) because options aren’t needed anymore.

After this step → data transfer can start.

2. Viewing This in Wireshark
Go to:

Statistics → Flow Graph → TCP flow

This graph shows:

First 3 packets = Handshake

Middle packets = Data exchange

Last 4 packets = Connection Teardown

3. Data Exchange Phase

This is where actual application-layer content is exchanged:

Example:

HTTP requests/responses

FTP commands

QUIT messages (in your capture)

You’ll see packets with:

ACKs

PSH flags

Sequence and ACK numbers increasing

TCP payload (data)

No handshake/teardown flags appear here.

4. TCP Teardown (4-Way Termination)

When either side finishes sending data, they close the connection using a four-packet FIN sequence.

The sequence is:

Step 1 — FIN-ACK (Server → Client)

Server says: “I’m done sending data. Let’s close.”

Flags: FIN = 1, ACK = 1

Step 2 — ACK (Client → Server)

Client acknowledges server’s FIN:
“Okay, I got your FIN.”

Step 3 — FIN-ACK (Client → Server)

Client also sends FIN:
“I’m done too.”

Step 4 — Final ACK (Server → Client)

Server acknowledges client’s FIN.

Connection is now fully closed.

You’ll see these as the last four packets in Wireshark.

5. Why FIN needs 4 packets (not 3 like SYN)?

Because FIN is one-directional:

Each side independently tells the other that it is done sending data.
Handshake is mutual (bidirectional), but close is separate.

6. Why no Data in Handshake Packets?

Handshakes only exchange control information, not user data.
Therefore:

Length = 0

No TCP payload

Only headers + options

7. Summary Table (Easy to Memorize)
Phase	Packet	Flags	Meaning
Handshake	SYN	SYN	Client → Server: Start connection
	SYN-ACK	SYN, ACK	Server → Client: Acknowledge and accept
	ACK	ACK	Client → Server: Connection established
Teardown	FIN-ACK	FIN, ACK	First side ends connection
	ACK	ACK	Other side acknowledges FIN
	FIN-ACK	FIN, ACK	Second side ends connection
	ACK	ACK	Final ACK: connection closed
8. What to Look for in Wireshark (Checklist for Exams/Labs)
Handshake

✔ SYN
✔ SYN-ACK
✔ ACK
✔ TCP Options (MSS, WS, SACK, TS, NOP)
✔ Header size > 20 bytes

Data Exchange

✔ PSH/ACK
✔ Increasing sequence/ack numbers
✔ TCP payload visible

Teardown

✔ FIN-ACK
✔ ACK
✔ FIN-ACK
✔ Final ACK
✔ No RST (reset) unless abnormal close

9. One-Line Explanation for Each Packet (What to Write in Labs)

Packet 1 (SYN):
Client initiates the connection and proposes TCP options.

Packet 2 (SYN-ACK):
Server accepts and responds with its own options.

Packet 3 (ACK):
Client completes handshake; connection established.

Data packets:
Bi-directional exchange of application data with ACKs.

FIN-ACK (Server):
Server begins orderly shutdown.

ACK (Client):
Client acknowledges server’s FIN.

FIN-ACK (Client):
Client ends its side of the conversation.

Final ACK (Server):
Server confirms and terminates session.
